<lg id="t.6.1.11.4" type="proverb" n="11.4"><p id="t6111.p1" n="5" corresp="c6111.A.11.4.5">
&X;&X; the storehouse &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.5" type="proverb" n="11.5"><p id="t6111.p2" n="6-7" corresp="c6111.A.11.5.6">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.55">6.1.03.55</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.07" from="t.6.1.07.48">6.1.07.48</xref></note>
As long as you live you should not increase evil by lying; for if you do, to succumb will be your lot.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.6" type="proverb" n="11.6"><p id="t6111.p3" n="8-9" corresp="c6111.A.11.6.8">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.133">6.1.02.133</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.22">6.1.22: l. 80</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.26" from="t.6.1.26.d3">6.1.26.d3</xref></note>
To collect firewood is a job for the strong man. The weak man sits waiting for him on dry land.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.7" type="proverb" n="11.7"><p id="t6111.p4" n="10-13" corresp="c6111.A.11.7.10">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.150">6.1.01.150</xref></note>
<gap extent="1 line unclear"/>
Let an articulate man live in the house with you like a wicked poor man. Like my own affairs, antimony paste (?) is air: let &X;&X; fat be eaten in the mist.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.8" type="proverb" n="11.8"><p id="t6111.p5" n="14-15" corresp="c6111.A.11.8.14">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.103">6.1.02.103</xref></note>
Although the lamentation priest's grain boat was sinking, he would be walking on dry land.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.9" type="proverb" n="11.9"><p id="t6111.p6" n="16-18" corresp="c6111.A.11.9.16">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.103">6.1.02.103</xref></note>
<w type="DN">Enki</w>
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.10" type="proverb" n="11.10"><p id="t6111.p7" n="19-23" corresp="c6111.A.11.10.19">
<gap extent="5 lines fragmentary"/>
<gap extent="approx. 14 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="B">
<lg id="t.6.1.11.18" type="proverb" n="11.18"><p id="t6111.p8" n="1-5" corresp="c6111.B.11.18.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.31">6.1.03.31</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.09" from="t.6.1.09.b1">6.1.09.b1</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.15" from="t.6.1.15.b8">6.1.15.b8</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.4">6.1.25.4</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.1">6.2.1: Ni 4469 Seg. A ll. 9-12</xref></note>
<w type="RN">Nanni</w> appreciated his old age. He built <w type="DN">Enlil's</w> temple but did not complete it. He built a wall around <w type="SN">Nibru</w>, but &X;&X;. He captured <w type="SN">Simurrum</w>, but did not suppress it. In misery he &X;&X;. Thus <w type="RN">Nanni</w> was brought to the nether world depressed at heart.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.19" type="proverb" n="11.19"><p id="t6111.p9" n="6-7" corresp="c6111.B.11.19.6">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.71">6.1.03.71</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.19" from="t.6.1.19.b6">6.1.19.b6</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.24" from="t.6.1.24.5">6.1.24.5</xref></note>
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/>
&X;&X; its hands &X;&X; to the edge of the desert.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.20" type="proverb" n="11.20"><p id="t6111.p10" n="8" corresp="c6111.B.11.20.8">
When it stretches, it &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.21" type="proverb" n="11.21"><p id="t6111.p11" n="9-10" corresp="c6111.B.11.21.9">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.07" from="t.6.1.07.41">6.1.07.41</xref></note>
He spoke but did not keep his word. He keeps speaking but shies away from his responsibilities.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.22" type="proverb" n="11.22"><p id="t6111.p12" n="11-12" corresp="c6111.B.11.22.11">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.69">6.1.03.69</xref></note>
He who insults is insulted. He who sneers is sneered at.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.23" type="proverb" n="11.23"><p id="t6111.p13" n="13" corresp="c6111.B.11.23.13">
So says the slave girl: <q>It has been carried away!</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.24" type="proverb" n="11.24"><p id="t6111.p14" n="14" corresp="c6111.B.11.24.14">
<q>Let the master's god split it, then.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.25" type="proverb" n="11.25"><p id="t6111.p15" n="15" corresp="c6111.B.11.25.15">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.89">6.1.03.89</xref></note>
The overseer does not know how to assign the work and so cannot stop the trembling (?).</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.26A" type="proverb" n="11.26A"><p id="t6111.p16" n="16" corresp="c6111.B.11.26.16">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.d7">6.1.02.d7</xref></note>
Now, you should not sleep in the reedbeds.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.26B" type="proverb" n="11.26B"><p id="t6111.p17" n="17" corresp="c6111.B.11.26.17">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.d7">6.1.02.d7</xref></note>
The rats of the reedbeds will eat you.
<gap extent="approx. 5 lines missing"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.29" type="proverb" n="11.29"><p id="t6111.p18" n="23-26" corresp="c6111.B.11.29.23">
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/>
&X;&X; guard &X;&X; reach out to you &X;&X;.
<gap extent="approx. 21 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="C">
<lg id="t.6.1.11.35" type="proverb" n="11.35"><p id="t6111.p19" n="1" corresp="c6111.C.11.35.1">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.36" type="proverb" n="11.36"><p id="t6111.p20" n="2" corresp="c6111.C.11.36.2">
<gap extent="1 line missing"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.37" type="proverb" n="11.37"><p id="t6111.p21" n="3" corresp="c6111.C.11.37.3">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.38" type="proverb" n="11.38"><p id="t6111.p22" n="4-5" corresp="c6111.C.11.38.4">
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.39" type="proverb" n="11.39"><p id="t6111.p23" n="6-8" corresp="c6111.C.11.39.6">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.109">6.1.01.109</xref></note>
You cannot butt me with your horns! Why are you butting? I am running away!</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.40" type="proverb" n="11.40"><p id="t6111.p24" n="9-11" corresp="c6111.C.11.40.9">
Like a tall person &X;&X; not &X;&X; lifting &X;&X; lifting.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.41" type="proverb" n="11.41"><p id="t6111.p25" n="12-14" corresp="c6111.C.11.41.12">
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/>
Letting water flow into the dykes
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.42" type="proverb" n="11.42"><p id="t6111.p26" n="15" corresp="c6111.C.11.42.15">
A <foreign lang="sux">gir</foreign> fish of the sea, whose head is wider than its body.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.43" type="proverb" n="11.43"><p id="t6111.p27" n="16" corresp="c6111.C.11.43.16">
From the river, oh <w type="DN">Inana</w>, let my man eat.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.44" type="proverb" n="11.44"><p id="t6111.p28" n="17" corresp="c6111.C.11.44.17">
Rats dig the ground.
<gap extent="approx. 24 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="D">
<lg id="t.6.1.11.51" type="proverb" n="11.51"><p id="t6111.p29" n="1-3" corresp="c6111.D.11.51.1">
<gap extent="3 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.52" type="proverb" n="11.52"><p id="t6111.p30" n="4-5" corresp="c6111.D.11.52.4">
<q>My affairs are great affairs, my offices are great offices.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.53" type="proverb" n="11.53"><p id="t6111.p31" n="6-7" corresp="c6111.D.11.53.6">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.97">6.1.01.97</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.07" from="t.6.1.07.104">6.1.07.104</xref></note>
An exciteable man should not become an overseer. A shepherd should not become a farmer.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.54" type="proverb" n="11.54"><p id="t6111.p32" n="8" corresp="c6111.D.11.54.8">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.104">6.1.01.104</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.15" from="t.6.1.15.c3">6.1.15.c3</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.26" from="t.6.1.26.b4">6.1.26.b4</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.28" from="t.6.1.28.8">6.1.28.8</xref></note>
Were you to pour oil onto the top of a sceptre.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.55" type="proverb" n="11.55"><p id="t6111.p33" n="9" corresp="c6111.D.11.55.9">
From within a tree, a spoon. Who is it?</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.56" type="proverb" n="11.56"><p id="t6111.p34" n="10" corresp="c6111.D.11.56.10">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.25" from="t.6.1.25.9">6.1.25.9</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.26" from="t.6.1.26.a2">6.1.26.a2</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. B l. 2</xref></note>
A palace will fall of its own accord.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.57" type="proverb" n="11.57"><p id="t6111.p35" n="11-12" corresp="c6111.D.11.57.11">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.18" from="t.6.1.18.15">6.1.18.15</xref></note>
Oh whirlwind, I despatched you towards <w type="SN">Agade</w>. What did you accomplish in <w type="SN">Agade</w>? The dream was favourable!
<gap extent="approx. 26 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="E">
<lg id="t.6.1.11.66" type="proverb" n="11.66"><p id="t6111.p36" n="1" corresp="c6111.E.11.66.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.26" from="t.6.1.26.a6">6.1.26.a6</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. B l. 6</xref></note>
To take revenge is the prerogative of <w type="DN">Ninurta</w>.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.67" type="proverb" n="11.67"><p id="t6111.p37" n="2-3" corresp="c6111.E.11.67.2">
<q>That my friend should be well is our wish, and that our enemies should be gone! May those friendly to you reach their goal as a ship does a friendly harbour!</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.68" type="proverb" n="11.68"><p id="t6111.p38" n="4" corresp="c6111.E.11.68.4">
<q>May your enemy, like the flood waters of a river, return to his city.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.69" type="proverb" n="11.69"><p id="t6111.p39" n="5-6" corresp="c6111.E.11.69.5">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.149">6.1.02.149</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.26" from="t.6.1.26.d15">6.1.26.d15</xref></note>
Those who live near the water look into the mountains. They don't look in their own direction.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.70" type="proverb" n="11.70"><p id="t6111.p40" n="7-8" corresp="c6111.E.11.70.7">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.150">6.1.02.150</xref></note>
<w type="PN">Adapa</w> knows no loss as he walks within the mountains.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.71" type="proverb" n="11.71"><p id="t6111.p41" n="9-10" corresp="c6111.E.11.71.9">
Living is living. But to live (?) like (?) a lord!
<gap extent="approx. 30 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="F">
<lg id="t.6.1.11.82" type="proverb" n="11.82"><p id="t6111.p42" n="1-3" corresp="c6111.F.11.82.1">
<gap extent="3 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.83" type="proverb" n="11.83"><p id="t6111.p43" n="4-6" corresp="c6111.F.11.83.4">
<gap extent="3 lines missing"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.84" type="proverb" n="11.84"><p id="t6111.p44" n="7-11" corresp="c6111.F.11.84.7">
<gap extent="3 lines fragmentary"/>
&X;&X; merchant &X;&X; partner &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.85" type="proverb" n="11.85"><p id="t6111.p45" n="12-13" corresp="c6111.F.11.85.12">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.2.5" from="t625.h16">6.2.5: YBC 7345</xref></note>
The cripple (?) took a reed basket. For (?) his words a man beats him.
<gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="G">
