<gap extent="4 lines fragmentary"/><gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="I">
<lg id="t.6.1.11.130" type="proverb" n="11.130"><p id="t6111.p48" n="1-2" corresp="c6111.I.11.130.1">
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.131" type="proverb" n="11.131"><p id="t6111.p49" n="3-4" corresp="c6111.I.11.131.3">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.126">6.1.02.126</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.04" from="t.6.1.04.56">6.1.04.56</xref></note>
Says the man lying on the roof to the man living in the house: <q>It is too bright up here!</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.132" type="proverb" n="11.132"><p id="t6111.p50" n="5-6" corresp="c6111.I.11.132.5">
A distant (?) good word &X;&X; a cargo boat.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.133" type="proverb" n="11.133"><p id="t6111.p51" n="7-8" corresp="c6111.I.11.133.7">
Uncleared debts &X;&X; are something which makes debts to <w type="DN">Utu</w>.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.134" type="proverb" n="11.134"><p id="t6111.p52" n="9-12" corresp="c6111.I.11.134.9">
<gap extent="4 lines fragmentary"/>
<gap extent="approx. 29 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="J">
<lg id="t.6.1.11.146" type="proverb" n="11.146"><p id="t6111.p53" n="1-2" corresp="c6111.J.11.146.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.37">6.1.02.37</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.3">6.2.3: UET 6/2 267 ll. 1-2</xref></note>
You're a scribe but you don't even know how to write your own name? Shame on you!</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.147" type="proverb" n="11.147"><p id="t6111.p54" n="3" corresp="c6111.J.11.147.3">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.5.6.1">5.6.1: l. 202</xref></note>
A loving heart builds houses.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.148" type="proverb" n="11.148"><p id="t6111.p55" n="4" corresp="c6111.J.11.148.4">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.5.6.1">5.6.1: l. 203</xref></note>
A hating heart destroys houses.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.149" type="proverb" n="11.149"><p id="t6111.p56" n="5-6" corresp="c6111.J.11.149.5">
Her friend advises (?) her: <q>It is for your own good.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.150" type="proverb" n="11.150"><p id="t6111.p57" n="7" corresp="c6111.J.11.150.7">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.5.6.1">5.6.1: l. 208</xref></note>
Don't choose a wife during a festival!
<gap extent="approx. 30 lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="K">
<lg id="t.6.1.11.160" type="proverb" n="11.160"><p id="t6111.p58" n="1-2" corresp="c6111.K.11.160.1">
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.161" type="proverb" n="11.161"><p id="t6111.p59" n="3" corresp="c6111.K.11.161.3">
You cool down their hearts.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.11.162" type="proverb" n="11.162"><p id="t6111.p60" n="4-8" corresp="c6111.K.11.162.4">
I am a capable scribe. There will be a prominent place for me. I will bring my &X;&X; protection &X;&X; to the stewardship.
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/>
<gap extent="approx. 18 lines missing"/></p>
